<subSubSection id="F89B26A3C9F80CFA37806B654A15AF55" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="7E26EFB000A09B7FE7D04BECF2AE69AD" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A9A293A30272C0B00C878B3F0641DEAE" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
This species and 
<taxonomicName id="5F5FDF151A23B02B2CCC2109A1DCF65A" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina buccata" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccata">Discocerina buccata</taxonomicName>
are apparently closely related, as evidenced by the high gena, which is unique within 
<taxonomicName id="5F23E372849C62E2044FC10A66B05CA4" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Discocerina</taxonomicName>
and which was also the reason why both species had been placed in 
<taxonomicName id="12A6831508F35634E705E00180DA3BF2" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Hydrochasma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrochasma" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hydrochasma</taxonomicName>
. Like 
<taxonomicName id="33BD7E3AAF4B851DBF0DFFE637A7E032" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina buccata" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccata">Discocerina buccata</taxonomicName>
and other congeners in 
<taxonomicName id="9F45DDC43BB2487799D1C0764C428F8B" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Discocerina</taxonomicName>
, however, 
<taxonomicName id="E9B8D8D351E70B50F95A711CABE02598" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina ceraceps" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceraceps">Discocerina ceraceps</taxonomicName>
has the phallapodeme fused with the base of the aedeagus, a synapomorphy for these species and other congeners in 
<taxonomicName id="8A799233672500545ED321223A583E40" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Discocerina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discocerina" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Discocerina</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
